St. Paul&rsquo;s University men&rsquo;s volleyball team beat Kenya College of Accountancy 3-0 to assume the leadership of Nairobi North Conference in the Kenya Universities Sports Association League at USIU over the weekend.The straight sets&rsquo; of 25-14, 25-22 and 25-19 over KCA-U saw the Limuru-based line-up move two places up, dethroning Jomo Kenyatta University of Agriculture and Technology at the top of the table with 12 points. St. Paul&rsquo;s were overly superior to their Thika Road counterparts in attacks and defence in the first set, but their own mistakes in the second period boosted KCA who came close (25-22) to snatching a set.The third set was anyone&rsquo;s game at the first technical time out as St. Paul&rsquo;s led KCA-U 8-7. Setter Brian Barasa came through for St. Paul&rsquo;s under former national team coach Sammy Kirongo, with two dodges and three aces to open the gap 14-9. St. Paul&rsquo;s maintained the momentum winning the third set 25-19 to seal the match 3-0.St. Paul&rsquo;s women&rsquo;s team, too, extended their unbeaten run with a 3-1 win against JKUAT. The team, which boosts the national women&rsquo;s under-23 setter Faith Imodia beat JKUAT in sets of 25-11, 17-25, 25-16 and 25-19 to top the log with 11 points from four matches.With a 3-0 (13-25, 16-25, 20-25) victory over KCA-U, Daystar University (women) ascends to position four with six points in the seven-team women&rsquo;s league. Mt. Kenya University displaced Kenyatta University in the second position after thwarting hosts USIU-A 3-2 (20-25, 25-18, 10-25, 25-21, 13-15).The other men&rsquo;s fixtures saw Mt. Kenya University (who finished 12/13 in the KVF national league) hammer KCA-U 3-1 (24-26, 25-18, 28-26, 25-23), and Daystar (main Campus) beat Club Gretsa in a five-set duel 22-25, 25-16, 19-25, 25-22 and 15-10.